Conference track information : http : / / cs . unomaha . edu / ~ rewini / SWT-CFP . html Minitrack information : http : / / www . cis . unisa . edu . au / events / hicss 33 / index . html Automated tools play an important role in the promotion and adoption of software engineering methods and processes , both within a particular organisation and within the software engineering community generally . The development of these tools is itself a significant software engineering task , requiring a considerable investment of time and resources . There are a large number of different kinds of automated software engineering tool , variously known as Computer Aided Software Engineering ( CASE ) , Computer Aided Method Engineering ( CAME ) , Integrated Project Support Environments ( IPSE ) , Software Engineering Environments ( SEE ) , and meta - CASE tools . Although these tools differ in the particular methods , activities , and phases of the software development cycle to which they are applied , developers of these tools often face similar implementation issues . Decisions about host computing platform , implementation language , conformance with standards and reference models , choice of repository , integration and interoperability mechanisms , and user interface style have to be made . This Minitrack will be based around the experience reports of researchers and practitioners actively involved in software engineering tool development . It should be of interest to anyone concerned with : - tool construction technologies and techniques ; - development and application of new tools ; - evaluation of tools . It is intended to cover a wide range software engineering tools , including : SEE , IPSE , CASE , CAME , CSCW , Workflow , and meta - CASE tools . The purpose of the minitrack is to bring together an international audience of researchers and practitioners with similar interests and experience . The minitrack will focus principally on practical issues such as implementation languages and platforms , repository organization , tool integration and interoperability , tool evaluation approaches , and tool development methods . This minitrack will be of interest to many practicing software engineers , and it should appeal to a wide range of HICSS delegates participating in the Software Technology track . A HICSS minitrack may be either a half-day or full-day stream of the conference . The minitrack consists of two or four 90 - minute sessions conducted in a workshop-like setting . Each session consists of three papers with each paper allotted thirty minutes for presentation and questions . The last session includes a forum which typically is a lively , open dialogue on the issues raised in the presentations . Papers accepted for presentation in the minitrack will appear in the HICSS- 33 Conference Proceedings published by IEEE Computer Society . Interested authors should submit a 300 - word plain text abstract to the minitrack coordinator before the full paper deadline , so that feedback on the appropriateness of the abstract can be sent to authors . . Submit eight ( 8 ) copies of the full manuscript by 1 June , 1999 . Manuscripts should have an abstract and be 22 - 25 typewritten , double-spaced pages in length . Papers must not have been previously presented or published , nor currently submitted for journal publication . Each manuscript will be subjected to a rigorous refereeing process . Individuals interested in refereeing papers should contact the minitrack coordinator directly , but authors may not act as a referee in the same HICSS minitrack .
